%description:
TCP AccECN (Workstream G) G9.1: fallback-matrix completeness --
tcpEcnMode="accecn-passive" as the ACTIVE OPENER role. Client is
accecn-passive; server is accecn. sendSyn()'s AccECN-initiate branch
(TcpConnectionUtil.cc) checks `state->ecnMode == TCP_ECN_MODE_ACCECN`
only, not ACCECN_PASSIVE, so an accecn-passive active opener sends a
plain SYN with no ECN codepoint at all (its own code comment: "covers
off, passive, and accecn-passive: none of these initiate on active
OPEN"). The server, seeing no ECN-willingness signal in the SYN at all,
negotiates no ECN either -- the two ends end up with NO ECN, not classic
ECN and not AccECN, even though the server itself is accecn-capable and
would have accepted a request. This is the accecn-passive design intent
(RFC 3168's own precedent: it only ever means "will respond to a peer's
request", never "will ask"), pinned here as the second half of
tcp_accecn_fallback_1.test's assertion (listener role, accepts) so the
mode's asymmetry is tested from both sides.

Falsification: none needed as a separate run -- the assertion (plain,
ECN-flag-less SYN despite both tcpEcnMode values being ECN-capable
modes) is itself the falsification of "accecn-passive negotiates
AccECN/ECN when possible regardless of role", the plausible-but-wrong
reading.

Building this test surfaced a real, pre-existing (not AccECN-related,
not touched by this workstream) quirk: sendSynAck()'s classic-ECN
branch (`else if (state->ecnWillingness)`, TcpConnectionUtil.cc) sets
the SYN-ACK's ECE bit purely from the SERVER's own willingness, without
checking whether the peer's SYN actually requested ECN
(endPointIsWillingECN) -- so the server's SYN-ACK here still carries ECE
even though the client's SYN was plain. Harmless in practice: the
client only acts on an incoming SYN-ACK's ECE bit if it itself sent an
ECN-setup SYN (state->ecnSynSent), which never happened here (its SYN
was plain, per the assertion above), so the client's ect stays false
and no ECN is actually used on this connection -- pinned below (A002,
the connection-completing ACK, carries no ECN flags). Out of scope to
fix as part of this AccECN-focused workstream; noted for a possible
future classic-ECN hardening pass, not filed as its own issue here.

%inifile: omnetpp.ini
[General]
record-vector-results = false
ned-path = .;../../../../src;../../lib

network = inet.test.moduletest.lib.TcpTestNet1

cmdenv-event-banners=false
cmdenv-express-mode=false
cmdenv-log-prefix="[%c]: "

*.testing=false
*.tcptester.script=""

*.cli_app.localAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.cli_app.localPort=1000
*.cli_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.cli_app.connectPort=2000
*.cli_app.active=true
*.cli_app.tOpen=0s
*.cli_app.tSend=-1s
*.cli_app.sendBytes=0B
*.cli_app.tClose=-1s
*.cli_app.sendScript=""

*.srv_app.localAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.srv_app.localPort=2000
*.srv_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.srv_app.connectPort=1000
*.srv_app.active=false
*.srv_app.tOpen=0s
*.srv_app.tSend=-1s
*.srv_app.sendBytes=0B
*.srv_app.tClose=-1s
*.srv_app.sendScript=""

*.*_tcp.sackSupport = false
*.*_tcp.windowScalingSupport = false
*.*_tcp.timestampSupport = false
*.*_tcp.mss = 1000
*.*_tcp.tcpAlgorithmClass = "TcpReno"

*.cli_tcp.tcpEcnMode = "accecn-passive"
*.srv_tcp.tcpEcnMode = "accecn"

include ../../lib/tcp-legacy.ini

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: postrun.pl
open FILE, '<test.out';
while($sor = <FILE>)
{
    if ($sor =~ /^\[testing\]: (.*)$/)
    {
        print "$1\n";
    }
}
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command:  perl ./postrun.pl
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Client's SYN: plain, no ECN codepoint at all -- accecn-passive never initiates.
%contains: postrun-command(1).out
[0.001 A001] A.1000 > B.2000: S 0:0(0) win 7504   Option(s): MaxSegSize
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Server's SYN-ACK: still carries ECE (the pre-existing quirk described above) -- but since
%# the client's own SYN was plain, the client never acts on it (see A002 below).
%contains: postrun-command(1).out
[0.003 B001] A.1000 < B.2000: A S E 500:500(0) ack 1 win 7504   Option(s): MaxSegSize
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Client's connection-completing ACK: no ECN flags -- confirms ECN was never actually enabled
%# on this connection despite the server's inappropriate ECE offer above.
%contains: postrun-command(1).out
[0.005 A002] A.1000 > B.2000: A ack 501 win 7504
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
